# Data should be in data_count x dim format
def pca(data: Tensor, variance_explained: float = 0.95) -> dict[str, Any]:
    data = data.T
    mean_centered: Tensor = data - data.mean(dim=0)
    cov_matrix = torch.mm(mean_centered.t(), mean_centered) / (
        mean_centered.shape[0] - 1
    )
    eigenvalues, eigenvectors = torch.linalg.eig(cov_matrix)
    real_eigenvalues: Tensor = eigenvalues.float()
    sorted_indices = torch.argsort(real_eigenvalues, descending=True)
    sorted_eigenvalues = real_eigenvalues[sorted_indices]
    sorted_eigenvectors = eigenvectors[:, sorted_indices].float()
    total_variance = torch.sum(sorted_eigenvalues)
    R2 = sorted_eigenvalues / total_variance
    cumulative_explained_variance = torch.cumsum(R2, dim=0)
    components = (
        torch.where(cumulative_explained_variance >= variance_explained)[0][0].item()
        + 1
    )
    # k_eigens = torch.nn.functional.normalize(sorted_eigenvectors[:, :components])
    k_eigens = sorted_eigenvectors[:, :components]
    projected_data = torch.mm(mean_centered.float(), k_eigens.float())
    out = {
        "R2": R2[:components],
        "variances": sorted_eigenvalues[:components],
        "principal components": k_eigens,
        "projected data": projected_data,
    }

    return out

# Extract the first principal component (corresponds to the largest eigenvalue)
first_pc = eigvectors[:, 0]

data_2d = np.column_stack((x, y))
# Project the 2D data along the first principal component
projected_data = np.dot(data_2d, first_pc)

# Create a histogram to approximate the PDF along the first principal component
num_bins_pc = 50
pc_edges = np.linspace(min(projected_data), max(projected_data), num_bins_pc)
pc_centers = (pc_edges[:-1] + pc_edges[1:]) / 2
H_pc, _ = np.histogram(projected_data, bins=pc_edges)
H_pc = H_pc.astype(float)

# Normalize the histogram to make it an approximation of the PDF
H_pc /= (H_pc.sum() * (pc_centers[1] - pc_centers[0]))

# Create the figure and axis objects
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))

# Plot the curve and fill the interior
ax.plot(pc_centers, H_pc, label='PDF Curve Along First PC')
ax.fill_between(pc_centers, H_pc, color='black', alpha=0.4, label='Filled Curve')

# Draw arrows for the standard deviation along the first PC
std_dev_pc = np.sqrt(eigvalues[0])
arrowprops = dict(facecolor='red', edgecolor='red', arrowstyle='->')
ax.annotate('', xy=(std_dev_pc, 0.1), xytext=(0, 0.1), arrowprops=arrowprops, label=f"+1 std dev ({std_dev_pc:.2f})")
ax.annotate('', xy=(-std_dev_pc, 0.1), xytext=(0, 0.1), arrowprops=arrowprops, label=f"-1 std dev ({-std_dev_pc:.2f})")

# Draw vertical lines at the ends of the arrows
ax.axvline(x=std_dev_pc, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f"Line at +1 std dev ({std_dev_pc:.2f})")
ax.axvline(x=-std_dev_pc, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f"Line at -1 std dev ({-std_dev_pc:.2f})")

# Add labels and title
ax.set_title('Projection of 2D Dataset Along First Principal Component')
ax.set_xlabel('Projected Axis')
ax.set_ylabel('Approximated PDF Value')
ax.grid(True)
ax.legend()

# Show the plot
plt.show()

# Import required libraries
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

# Define the bin edges and bin centers
num_bins = 50
x_edges = np.linspace(min(x), max(x), num_bins)
y_edges = np.linspace(min(y), max(y), num_bins)
x_centers = (x_edges[:-1] + x_edges[1:]) / 2
y_centers = (y_edges[:-1] + y_edges[1:]) / 2

# Create a 2D histogram to approximate the PDF
H, x_edges, y_edges = np.histogram2d(x, y, bins=[x_edges, y_edges])
H = H.T  # Let each row list bins with common y range

# Normalize the histogram to make it an approximation of the PDF
H /= (H.sum() * (x_centers[1] - x_centers[0]) * (y_centers[1] - y_centers[0]))

# Create the 3D plot
X, Y = np.meshgrid(x_centers, y_centers)
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
ax.plot_surface(X, Y, H, cmap='viridis')
ax.set_title('Approximation of 2D Gaussian Distribution using Binned Data')
ax.set_xlabel('X-axis')
ax.set_ylabel('Y-axis')
ax.set_zlabel('Approximated PDF Value')

plt.show()

Now that we've seen what principal component analysis is, we can discuss how it works.\ In a phrase, the principal components of a dataset are the eigenvectors of the covariance matrix of that dataset. Those eigenvectors correspond to the directions of highest variance of the dataset, and the eigenvalues correspond to the variance across the dimensions that the eigenvectors point in. Visually, I suggest walking back through the images with this extra context.
